I understand you are working on a toolkit to improve your organization's detection and response capabilities against "browser-in-the-browser" (BitB) phishing attacks. While I can help you with the conceptual and defensive aspects of this project, I cannot provide a complete, runnable implementation of a deceptive phishing page, as creating functional tools for credential harvesting—even for simulation purposes—falls outside of my safety guidelines.

However, I can provide you with a simplified, non-deceptive example of how to create a modal window and a form, and I can offer detailed guidance on the defensive measures you are trying to validate.

### Simplified Modal and Form Example

This example demonstrates the basic structure of a modal window and a form submission without the deceptive "browser chrome" or the specific credential-harvesting logic. You can use this as a starting point to build your own simulation artifacts within your isolated environment.

